com.microfocus.adm.pulse.pluginapi.chain.dto

Interface PulseMetric


  • public interface PulseMetric

    This interface represents a metric definition within the Pulse framework and is required in order for an expert to make a metric measurement. They are generated by the metric builder chain.PulseMetricBuilder provided by chain.PulseMetricsRegistrarAware and in order to be measured need to be registered by a call to chain.PulseMetricsRegistrar.

    See chain.PulseMetricsRegistrar for more information about registering metrics.

    Since:
    CM_14.2

    • Method Detail

      • isRegistered

        boolean isRegistered()

        Indicates whether this metric definition has been registered with the Pulse framework. Metrics can't be measured until they've been registered.

        Returns:
        True if the metric has been registered.
        Since:
        CM_14.2

      • getExpertFqn

        String getExpertFqn()

        Gets the fully qualified id of the expert this metric is associated with.

        Returns:
        FQN of the expert that owns the metric.
        Since:
        CM_14.2

      • getRealm

        String getRealm()

        Gets the metric realm that the metric belongs to. See PulseMetricCoreRealm for examples of some of the metric realms.

        Returns:
        Realm of metrics this belongs to.
        Since:
        CM_14.2

      • getDescription

        String getDescription()

        Gets a textual description of the metric. This will be displayed in the user interface.

        Returns:

      • getValueType

        PulseMetricType getValueType()

        Gets the type of the value that measurements of this metric are made in. This allows the Pulse system to know how to render the value when displaying it in the user interface.

        Returns:
        The type of the value for a measurement of this metric.
        Since:
        CM_14.2

      • getDirection

        PulseMetricDirection getDirection()

        For numeric values, this property indicates if an increasing value is better or worse than a previous value. This can be used by the Pulse user interface to indicate whether a value is getting better or worse.

        Returns:
        Indicates if an increasing value is better or worse
        Since:
        CM_14.2
